but he had to push it.

1222
00:46:32,623 --> 00:46:35,425
You can hold the top and eat it slowly.

1223
00:46:35,492 --> 00:46:36,794
Should she use her hand?

1224
00:46:36,860 --> 00:46:39,163
-Yes, that was why I prepared the towel.
-Is this the top?

1225
00:46:39,563 --> 00:46:41,398
HOLDING IT WITH HER HAND

1226
00:46:42,332 --> 00:46:43,200
A BITE

1227
00:46:43,267 --> 00:46:44,568
The appetizer.

1228
00:46:44,635 --> 00:46:45,936
-Wow.
-It sounds so nice.

1229
00:46:46,003 --> 00:46:47,304
What's that at the bottom?

1230
00:46:47,371 --> 00:46:49,473
-It's romaine lettuce.
-Romaine.

1231
00:46:49,540 --> 00:46:52,476
The core is the crunchiest and sweetest.

1232
00:46:52,543 --> 00:46:54,178
So I cut out just the core.

1233
00:46:54,244 --> 00:46:55,746
Scallop tartare.

1234
00:46:55,813 --> 00:46:57,948
It was a surprise that he used

1235
00:46:58,015 --> 00:47:00,350
this portion of the romaine lettuce.

1236
00:47:00,417 --> 00:47:01,852
It's so good.

1237
00:47:01,919 --> 00:47:04,888
The core is tender,
yet it has a crunchy texture.

1238
00:47:04,955 --> 00:47:07,524
-That's why it sounds crunchy.
-You're right.

1239
00:47:07,591 --> 00:47:08,792
-Just like napa cabbage.
-Yes.

1240
00:47:08,859 --> 00:47:10,460
-It's the crunchiest.
-It wasn't even fried.

1241
00:47:10,527 --> 00:47:11,495
Like spring cabbage.

1242
00:47:11,562 --> 00:47:14,531
I marinated the scallops for a bit
with olive oil and salt.

1243
00:47:14,598 --> 00:47:17,835
-He served it with Swiss cheese.
-Cheese?

1244
00:47:17,901 --> 00:47:19,169
I love the balance.

1245
00:47:19,236 --> 00:47:20,304
The cheese at the bottom.

1246
00:47:20,370 --> 00:47:23,373
When something's really good,
her eyebrows turn into a mountain.

1247
00:47:23,440 --> 00:47:25,976
-I see.
-And she's doing it. It must be good.

1248
00:47:26,043 --> 00:47:28,345
-She's doing this with her eyebrows.
-Yes, it's good.

1249
00:47:28,412 --> 00:47:32,916
-The dish has a good rhythm.
-A good rhythm?

1250
00:47:32,983 --> 00:47:35,686
-That's a great expression. The rhythm.
-The rhythm.

1251
00:47:35,752 --> 00:47:38,689
An appetizer with a good rhythm
for the singer.

1252
00:47:38,755 --> 00:47:40,390
ARE YOU FINISHED? EXCUSE ME

1253
00:47:40,457 --> 00:47:41,291
LET ME REMOVE IT

1254
00:47:41,725 --> 00:47:43,827
DID YOU SEE THAT? HE DID THIS

1255
00:47:43,894 --> 00:47:45,829
LIKE THIS?

1256
00:47:45,896 --> 00:47:48,899
-The second course, sea urchin roe toast.
-Okay.

1257
00:47:49,333 --> 00:47:51,001
YUM

1258
00:47:51,068 --> 00:47:52,970
ENVIOUS

1259
00:47:53,036 --> 00:47:55,806
I'm fine. It feels like you're teasing me.

1260
00:47:55,873 --> 00:47:58,942
I also heard a crunch from the toast.

1261
00:47:59,009 --> 00:48:00,444
What's it like?

1262
00:48:00,510 --> 00:48:02,980
It's so odd that sea urchin roe

1263
00:48:03,046 --> 00:48:05,415
does not feel overly rich.

1264
00:48:05,482 --> 00:48:08,218
He made this with butter,

1265
00:48:08,285 --> 00:48:10,687
so I thought it could be too greasy.

1266
00:48:10,754 --> 00:48:12,089
But it's really refreshing.

1267
00:48:12,155 --> 00:48:15,225
-Because he made it crispy.
-Or is it the almonds?

1268
00:48:15,292 --> 00:48:18,028
The crispy texture
can help alleviate the richness.

1269
00:48:18,095 --> 00:48:21,064
-Mmm.
-Actually, I added a bit of sugar.

1270
00:48:21,131 --> 00:48:22,900
-No wonder.
-I wanted to bring out the sweetness.

1271
00:48:22,966 --> 00:48:25,569
-He added sugar.
-Because you have a sweet tooth.

1272
00:48:26,536 --> 00:48:28,872
FINISHES THE LAST BITE

1273
00:48:28,939 --> 00:48:29,907
You look happy.

1274
00:48:29,973 --> 00:48:31,708
I am so happy.

1275
00:48:31,775 --> 00:48:34,311
-Those were just appetizers.
-It's just the beginning.

1276
00:48:34,378 --> 00:48:36,813
Now, the main dish.

1277
00:48:36,880 --> 00:48:38,248
Please mix it with the sauce.

1278
00:48:38,315 --> 00:48:39,449
Keep mixing it.

1279
00:48:39,516 --> 00:48:41,551
-She has to <i>mantecare</i> it?
-Mix it up.

1280
00:48:41,618 --> 00:48:43,921
-Self-<i>mantecare.</i>
-Self-<i>mantecare.</i>

1281
00:48:43,987 --> 00:48:45,923
That's a nice bowl.

1282
00:48:45,989 --> 00:48:48,892
-You can't see anything from across.
-I can't see.

1283
00:48:48,959 --> 00:48:50,227
It makes you crave it less.

1284
00:48:50,294 --> 00:48:52,195
SUCCESSFULLY BLOCKS SIGHT

1285
00:48:52,262 --> 00:48:54,331
-You can't share it.
-It's only for you.

1286
00:48:54,398 --> 00:48:57,701
Tiffany's favorite pasta, <i>cacio e pepe</i>.

1287
00:48:57,768 --> 00:48:59,136
-A tough pasta to make.
-I'll try it.

1288
00:48:59,202 --> 00:49:01,571
-Simple dishes can be hard to make.
-That's true.

1289
00:49:01,638 --> 00:49:02,906
Was it cooked well?

1290
00:49:03,774 --> 00:49:05,342
-What's it like?
-It was burnt.

1291
00:49:05,409 --> 00:49:07,878
I wonder how it's cooked
and what the sauce is like.

1292
00:49:07,945 --> 00:49:09,546
She nods.

1293
00:49:10,414 --> 00:49:12,916
-It's his pasta. It must be perfect.
-I'm glad.

1294
00:49:14,885 --> 00:49:17,020
I think she senses something else
as she chews.

1295
00:49:17,087 --> 00:49:18,021
-Burnt?
-Is it burnt?

1296
00:49:18,088 --> 00:49:20,123
Is it charred <i>e pepe?</i>

1297
00:49:20,190 --> 00:49:22,125
-Charred <i>e pepe?</i>
-Charred<i> e pepe?</i>

1298
00:49:22,526 --> 00:49:23,393
NO

1299
00:49:23,460 --> 00:49:24,628
Charred <i>e pepe?</i>

1300
00:49:24,695 --> 00:49:26,063
Does it taste burnt?

1301
00:49:26,129 --> 00:49:27,197
It doesn't.

1302
00:49:27,264 --> 00:49:30,667
The ground pepper has
a strong presence overall,

1303
00:49:30,734 --> 00:49:33,470
so it's stinging my tongue a little.

1304
00:49:33,537 --> 00:49:35,439
-It's that spicy?
-Yes.

1305
00:49:35,505 --> 00:49:37,107
Hyo-yeon would love that.

1306
00:49:37,174 --> 00:49:39,443
-I would love that.
-You'd love it.

1307
00:49:39,509 --> 00:49:41,111
-I love ground pepper.
-She would.

1308
00:49:41,178 --> 00:49:43,447
-You'd love it.
-She likes strong spices.

1309
00:49:43,513 --> 00:49:45,349
Was that dish meant for next week?

1310
00:49:46,483 --> 00:49:47,317
HIS MISTAKE

1311
00:49:47,384 --> 00:49:49,019
You can try the dessert.

1312
00:49:49,086 --> 00:49:51,722
-He kept it in the freezer.
-Here comes the dessert.

1313
00:49:51,788 --> 00:49:53,256
Sam serves it himself.

1314
00:49:53,323 --> 00:49:55,625
-It looks delicate.
-It looks so pretty.

1315
00:49:55,692 --> 00:49:58,695
-It must look pretty too.
-It is.

1316
00:49:58,762 --> 00:50:01,598
Tiffany said she loves ice cream.

1317
00:50:01,665 --> 00:50:02,866
WILL IT PLEASE THE DESSERT LOVER?

1318
00:50:02,933 --> 00:50:04,701
Does persimmon go well with that?

1319
00:50:06,470 --> 00:50:07,404
It's so good.

1320
00:50:08,872 --> 00:50:10,107
It's really good.

1321
00:50:10,874 --> 00:50:13,810
Also, all of his dishes

1322
00:50:13,877 --> 00:50:15,612
have a really good rhythm.

1323
00:50:16,246 --> 00:50:18,582
At first, the texture is creamy,

1324
00:50:18,648 --> 00:50:19,716
then something's crunchy.

1325
00:50:19,783 --> 00:50:22,419
The crunchy topping is sliced thinly,

1326
00:50:22,486 --> 00:50:24,721
so it almost feels like gummy candy.

1327
00:50:24,788 --> 00:50:25,622
That adds fun.

1328
00:50:25,689 --> 00:50:27,758
It's a treat inside her mouth.

1329
00:50:27,824 --> 00:50:29,559
She says it has a good rhythm.

1330
00:50:29,626 --> 00:50:31,995
The ground pepper was too spicy,
so that must be so good.

1331
00:50:32,062 --> 00:50:34,598
-Was that his plan?
-It was.

1332
00:50:34,664 --> 00:50:35,732
-It was?
-He planned it.

1333
00:50:35,799 --> 00:50:37,401
-It's like a refresher.
-After the main dish,

1334
00:50:37,467 --> 00:50:38,802
-that must be good.
-It's so good.

1335
00:50:38,869 --> 00:50:40,303
"It's so good."

1336
00:50:40,370 --> 00:50:42,272
She needs to move on
to the next set of dishes.

1337
00:50:42,339 --> 00:50:44,608
-That's all for now.
-Yes.

1338
00:50:44,674 --> 00:50:46,710
Next, Chef Jong-won's dish.

1339
00:50:46,777 --> 00:50:48,578
Tiffany's Breakfast at Tiffany's.

1340
00:50:48,812 --> 00:50:52,249
SEA URCHIN ROE FRENCH TOAST

1341
00:50:52,516 --> 00:50:54,284
EGG CUSTARD

1342
00:50:54,351 --> 00:50:56,153
MINT CHOCOLATE RICE PUDDING

1343
00:50:56,820 --> 00:50:59,389
GRILLED SCALLOPS

1344
00:50:59,956 --> 00:51:03,860
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S
TIFFANY'S BREAKFAST AT TIFFANY'S

1345
00:51:03,927 --> 00:51:05,629
There's pasta in front of her…

1346
00:51:05,695 --> 00:51:08,865
-Every chef on that side is on the move.
-Thank you.

1347
00:51:09,699 --> 00:51:10,634
MOVING IN A LINE

1348
00:51:10,700 --> 00:51:13,336
-They're our chefs.
-I've seen this!

1349
00:51:13,403 --> 00:51:16,139
This happens to royalty
in other countries!

1350
00:51:16,206 --> 00:51:19,276
-I feel like I've become Audrey Hepburn.
-You have to put it down at once.

1351
00:51:19,342 --> 00:51:20,677
The fine dining restaurant style.

1352
00:51:20,744 --> 00:51:23,213
-One, two, three.
-One, two, three.

1353
00:51:26,149 --> 00:51:27,684
ALL AT ONCE

1354
00:51:28,285 --> 00:51:29,853
They must be a team.

1355
00:51:30,787 --> 00:51:33,223
RETURNING

1356
00:51:33,290 --> 00:51:35,258
They're a team,
but must be of different nationals.

1357
00:51:37,494 --> 00:51:39,629
-And different looks.
-You all look different too.

1358
00:51:39,696 --> 00:51:41,164
-Totally.
-Such an odd mix.

1359
00:51:41,231 --> 00:51:42,466
How should she begin?

1360
00:51:42,532 --> 00:51:45,469
I prepared champagne
for you to enjoy with it.

1361
00:51:45,535 --> 00:51:47,404
-Even champagne?
-I love it.

1362
00:51:47,471 --> 00:51:48,605
I got it out of your fridge.

1363
00:51:49,172 --> 00:51:51,608
-It's an emergency.
-Look at him go.

1364
00:51:51,675 --> 00:51:54,511
-Everything goes well with champagne.
-Every dish he made.

1365
00:51:54,578 --> 00:51:55,545
Egg, sea urchin roe.

1366
00:51:55,612 --> 00:51:58,281
The course will have
a great balance with champagne.

1367
00:51:58,348 --> 00:51:59,716
It'll balance out everything.

1368
00:51:59,783 --> 00:52:02,219
A glass of champagne
for the fine dining breakfast.

1369
00:52:02,285 --> 00:52:03,320
I'll pop one too.

1370
00:52:05,122 --> 00:52:06,423
Have a drink. Let's pop some soda.

1371
00:52:06,490 --> 00:52:07,691
I'll pop one too.

1372
00:52:09,593 --> 00:52:12,295
EVERYBODY, CHEERS

1373
00:52:12,362 --> 00:52:13,597
The flute is so pretty too.

1374
00:52:14,764 --> 00:52:16,600
We're all enjoying something carbonated.

1375
00:52:16,666 --> 00:52:19,269
Take the small spoon
and try the custard first.

1376
00:52:19,336 --> 00:52:20,637
Thank you.

1377
00:52:20,704 --> 00:52:22,506
There's sea urchin roe in there too.

1378
00:52:22,572 --> 00:52:24,374
-It'll go well.
-It must be so rich.

1379
00:52:24,441 --> 00:52:25,742
Egg and sea urchin roe is a win.

1380
00:52:26,510 --> 00:52:28,011
I wonder what the mix is like.

1381
00:52:30,413 --> 00:52:33,183
It must make her think a little.

1382
00:52:33,250 --> 00:52:35,118
The egg's texture is very fun.

1383
00:52:35,185 --> 00:52:36,386
-It's fun?
-Yes.

1384
00:52:36,453 --> 00:52:37,287
ANOTHER BITE

1385
00:52:37,854 --> 00:52:39,789
Sea urchin roe is smooth, right?

1386
00:52:39,856 --> 00:52:43,293
But it doesn't just feel smooth.

1387
00:52:43,360 --> 00:52:45,095
It's grainy in the mouth, yet soft.

1388
00:52:45,662 --> 00:52:47,164
It must feel like a slow song.

1389
00:52:47,230 --> 00:52:48,131
A little.

1390
00:52:54,437 --> 00:52:57,607
Next, please try the sourdough,
originated from San Francisco.

1391
00:52:57,674 --> 00:52:59,142
Try a bite of the French toast.

1392
00:52:59,209 --> 00:53:00,777
You topped it with sea urchin roe again.

1393
00:53:00,844 --> 00:53:03,180
I used the fish roe and Emmentaler.

1394
00:53:03,246 --> 00:53:04,681
You didn't cook the fish roe, right?

1395
00:53:04,748 --> 00:53:06,016
No, it's raw.

1396
00:53:06,082 --> 00:53:07,617
-It looks good.
-That one looks good.

1397
00:53:07,684 --> 00:53:10,187
Sam made toast too, so you can compare.

1398
00:53:10,253 --> 00:53:11,321
Yes, those are similar.

1399
00:53:11,388 --> 00:53:13,423
The difference is in almond and sugar.

1400
00:53:13,490 --> 00:53:14,658
Okay.

1401
00:53:14,724 --> 00:53:18,128
HOW DOES IT DIFFER FROM SAM'S TOAST?

1402
00:53:21,231 --> 00:53:22,799
Why are you so surprised?

1403
00:53:22,866 --> 00:53:26,336
Sourdough has the texture
that scrapes the top of your mouth.

1404
00:53:26,403 --> 00:53:27,671
But this isn't like that.

1405
00:53:27,737 --> 00:53:30,540
-He cut out the tough parts.
-He cut them out.

1406
00:53:30,607 --> 00:53:32,075
So the mixture seeped inside.

1407
00:53:32,142 --> 00:53:33,843
It's really soft,

1408
00:53:33,910 --> 00:53:34,878
and really…

1409
00:53:35,545 --> 00:53:36,713
HMM

1410
00:53:37,614 --> 00:53:38,481
Really…

1411
00:53:42,085 --> 00:53:44,221
How do I say that in Korean?

1412
00:53:44,287 --> 00:53:45,622
Kyun, can you be her interpreter?

1413
00:53:45,689 --> 00:53:47,424
I understood that.

1414
00:53:47,490 --> 00:53:49,726
But we want to understand too.
What did she say?

1415
00:53:49,793 --> 00:53:52,829
This type of bread can feel heavy,

1416
00:53:53,396 --> 00:53:55,332
but there's a lot of room to breathe.

1417
00:53:55,398 --> 00:53:57,634
It feels airy,

1418
00:53:57,701 --> 00:53:59,469
so it goes well with this.

1419
00:53:59,536 --> 00:54:02,105
Sourdough has a light, airy interior.

1420
00:54:02,172 --> 00:54:03,006
It does.

1421
00:54:03,073 --> 00:54:06,209
The egg mix and fresh cream
seeped right into the holes.

1422
00:54:06,276 --> 00:54:07,744
MAKING THE TOAST SOFTER

1423
00:54:07,811 --> 00:54:09,446
She finishes everything.

1424
00:54:09,512 --> 00:54:10,914
She eats well.

1425
00:54:10,981 --> 00:54:13,149
I guess she means the bread is light.

1426
00:54:13,783 --> 00:54:14,884
MAY I PLEASE HAVE ONE BITE?

1427
00:54:14,951 --> 00:54:17,053
-It's good.
-Is it?

1428
00:54:17,120 --> 00:54:18,755
Callops, callops, scallops.

1429
00:54:18,822 --> 00:54:21,358
Scallops and champagne must be killer.

1430
00:54:21,424 --> 00:54:22,392
It's a perfect combo.

1431
00:54:22,459 --> 00:54:23,960
-It is.
-Perfect.

1432
00:54:24,027 --> 00:54:25,895
They'll go well together. The balance.

1433
00:54:25,962 --> 00:54:28,732
I made sea urchin roe butter
and cooked the scallops in it.

1434
00:54:28,798 --> 00:54:30,600
So it's not actually sea urchin roe,

1435
00:54:30,667 --> 00:54:32,235
-but it has the flavor.
-Yes, he did that.

1436
00:54:32,302 --> 00:54:34,638
THE CROSS SECTION LOOKS PERFECT

1437
00:54:34,704 --> 00:54:36,339
Try it with the lettuce.

1438
00:54:36,406 --> 00:54:37,641
I need to step out and eat.

1439
00:54:37,707 --> 00:54:39,209
Me too.

1440
00:54:39,276 --> 00:54:40,410
I'm getting hungry.

1441
00:54:40,910 --> 00:54:42,712
A BITE OF SCALLOP

1442
00:54:45,548 --> 00:54:46,950
Swallow it with a sip of champagne.

1443
00:54:47,917 --> 00:54:50,120
I SHALL DO THAT

1444
00:54:50,186 --> 00:54:52,389
Gosh. That must taste so good.

1445
00:54:52,455 --> 00:54:53,590
That's simply perfection.

1446
00:54:53,657 --> 00:54:56,793
-It is perfect.
-It's perfect.

1447
00:54:57,294 --> 00:54:58,428
It's so good.

1448
00:54:58,495 --> 00:55:00,597
It's grilled perfectly,

1449
00:55:00,664 --> 00:55:02,098
firm on the outside,

1450
00:55:02,165 --> 00:55:06,503
yet soft and bouncy on the inside.

1451
00:55:06,569 --> 00:55:09,172
It's grilled perfectly
to eat with champagne.

1452
00:55:14,144 --> 00:55:15,245
Is he going there to eat some?

1453
00:55:15,312 --> 00:55:17,647
-Are you stealing her food?
-No, it's the dessert spoon.

1454
00:55:17,714 --> 00:55:20,216
-You surprised me.
-I thought you were trying to eat some.

1455
00:55:20,283 --> 00:55:21,518
I thought you ran over to eat

1456
00:55:21,584 --> 00:55:23,920
-because you couldn't hold back.
-No, I'm good.

1457
00:55:23,987 --> 00:55:25,722
Thank you.

1458
00:55:25,789 --> 00:55:27,624
I thought,
"He can't even hold himself back."

1459
00:55:27,691 --> 00:55:29,059
I thought he had lost all reason.

1460
00:55:29,125 --> 00:55:31,628
I saw him running over and thought,
"Has he finally lost it?"

1461
00:55:31,695 --> 00:55:34,230
-"He can't go there and eat it."
-I mean, even if you want to.

1462
00:55:34,297 --> 00:55:36,566
He ran over way too quickly.

1463
00:55:36,633 --> 00:55:38,501
-Like a boar?
-I was surprised.

1464
00:55:38,568 --> 00:55:40,637
-The last one.
-The mint chocolate porridge.

1465
00:55:41,438 --> 00:55:43,506
Don't. Don't say it.

1466
00:55:43,573 --> 00:55:46,776
It may have changed
compared to when I had it before.

1467
00:55:46,843 --> 00:55:49,446
I sprinkled sugar on top and torched it.

1468
00:55:49,512 --> 00:55:51,247
I had it while it was boiling.

1469
00:55:51,314 --> 00:55:53,717
It smells really good.

1470
00:55:53,783 --> 00:55:56,086
-But it doesn't look so…
-The visual.

1471
00:55:56,152 --> 00:55:58,254
Did I inspire him?

1472
00:55:58,321 --> 00:56:00,690
I'm sorry for how it looks,
but I topped it with mint.

1473
00:56:00,757 --> 00:56:02,692
It's the same color
as <i>chueotang, </i>loach soup.

1474
00:56:02,759 --> 00:56:05,395
Or homemade <i>doenjang</i>.

1475
00:56:05,462 --> 00:56:08,998
-You can scoop it out and make soup.
-Or abalone porridge.

1476
00:56:09,065 --> 00:56:10,967
-The one made with the innards.
-Yes, the innards.

1477
00:56:11,034 --> 00:56:12,469
Listen to these two.

1478
00:56:12,535 --> 00:56:14,137
I said it because it looked good.

1479
00:56:14,204 --> 00:56:15,405
PRETENDING LIKE SHE DIDN'T

1480
00:56:15,705 --> 00:56:16,906
SCOOPING OUT

1481
00:56:16,973 --> 00:56:21,578
-What will she think of this?
-That absolutely shouldn't be good.

1482
00:56:21,644 --> 00:56:23,079
No, it'll be good.

1483
00:56:23,146 --> 00:56:24,280
I can't believe this.

1484
00:56:25,782 --> 00:56:28,184
-I'm curious.
-I'm a bit curious too.

1485
00:56:28,251 --> 00:56:29,386
-I'm dying to know.
-I can't explain.

1486
00:56:29,452 --> 00:56:30,387
-You can't?
-No.

1487
00:56:30,453 --> 00:56:31,654
Does it taste like mint chocolate?

1488
00:56:31,721 --> 00:56:33,289
It has the flavor.

1489
00:56:33,356 --> 00:56:35,392
But because of the rice,

1490
00:56:35,458 --> 00:56:38,495
it's luxurious
and the mint gives off a lot of aroma.

1491
00:56:38,561 --> 00:56:39,662
It's not like toothpaste.

1492
00:56:39,729 --> 00:56:43,333
Also, there's a pleasant
and subtle chocolate flavor too.

1493
00:56:43,400 --> 00:56:45,201
It's so odd.

1494
00:56:45,268 --> 00:56:47,537
Honestly speaking, the color

1495
00:56:47,604 --> 00:56:48,905
isn't really my style.

1496
00:56:49,472 --> 00:56:51,207
But it's so pretty. No.

1497
00:56:51,274 --> 00:56:52,809
It tastes so pretty.

1498
00:56:52,876 --> 00:56:55,578
The dessert must have a twist.

1499
00:56:55,645 --> 00:56:56,746
-It's tough to make.
-You hate that.

1500
00:56:56,813 --> 00:56:58,815
-It's so new.
-It's new?

1501
00:56:58,882 --> 00:57:00,417
Let me try some.

1502
00:57:01,084 --> 00:57:02,085
It tastes…

1503
00:57:03,086 --> 00:57:03,920
It smells sweet.

1504
00:57:04,754 --> 00:57:06,356
The color is like octopus and wasabi.

1505
00:57:06,423 --> 00:57:08,024
Because of the mint
chocolate chip ice cream.

1506
00:57:08,591 --> 00:57:10,226
What's it like?

1507
00:57:10,293 --> 00:57:11,194
-Isn't it good?
-Yes.

1508
00:57:11,761 --> 00:57:12,595
MMM!

1509
00:57:12,962 --> 00:57:14,297
Is it different from how it looks?

1510
00:57:14,364 --> 00:57:16,566
The mint doesn't feel too strong.

1511
00:57:16,633 --> 00:57:19,369
And once in a while,
the chocolate makes itself noticeable,

1512
00:57:19,436 --> 00:57:20,937
while the rice feels chewy.

1513
00:57:21,738 --> 00:57:22,772
I'M GLAD

1514
00:57:22,839 --> 00:57:24,207
You can taste the mint,

1515
00:57:24,274 --> 00:57:26,109
while the chocolate comes in a beat after.

1516
00:57:26,176 --> 00:57:27,811
-A beat after?
-A layback.

1517
00:57:27,877 --> 00:57:30,246
-A layback.
-A beat after?

1518
00:57:30,313 --> 00:57:32,449
It comes in a beat after.

1519
00:57:32,515 --> 00:57:34,284
Even if you don't like mint chocolate,

1520
00:57:34,350 --> 00:57:36,786
this can turn you into a lover.

1521
00:57:36,853 --> 00:57:39,055
It doesn't taste like mint chocolate.

1522
00:57:39,122 --> 00:57:41,758
It excludes the bad flavors
of mint chocolate.

1523
00:57:41,991 --> 00:57:43,593
THE BAD FLAVORS?

1524
00:57:43,660 --> 00:57:46,029
-Yes.
-The bad flavors? Let's debate that later.

1525
00:57:46,095 --> 00:57:47,230
LET'S HAVE A DEBATE NEXT TIME

1526
00:57:47,897 --> 00:57:50,166
-Chef Sam's dish.
-Chef Sam.

1527
00:57:50,834 --> 00:57:53,336
-She said it was spicy.
-Yes, the ground pepper.

1528
00:57:53,403 --> 00:57:56,339
Actually, this amount of ground pepper
is how I like it.

1529
00:57:57,307 --> 00:58:01,611
-It would've been too rich without it.
-I knew it.

1530
00:58:01,678 --> 00:58:04,881
But the amount of ground pepper
harmonizes everything.

1531
00:58:05,915 --> 00:58:08,117
I think I get why this pasta is so loved.

1532
00:58:08,184 --> 00:58:09,385
Is this your first time trying it?

1533
00:58:09,452 --> 00:58:11,187
Yes, <i>cacio</i>… Pacio?

1534
00:58:11,254 --> 00:58:13,556
-<i>Cacio e pepe</i>.
-<i>Cacio e pepe</i>.

1535
00:58:13,623 --> 00:58:16,659
-All right. Then please choose.
-It must be tough.

1536
00:58:16,726 --> 00:58:18,595
-Tiffany's choice.
-This is hard.

1537
00:58:18,661 --> 00:58:21,598
<i>Press one to choose</i>
<i>Tiffany's Breakfast at Tiffany's.</i>

1538
00:58:21,664 --> 00:58:24,033
<i>Press two to choose</i>
<i>Right Now, It's Sam's Generation.</i>

1539
00:58:24,100 --> 00:58:25,668
You may only choose one.

1540
00:58:26,402 --> 00:58:27,370
Did you pick one?

1541
00:58:28,204 --> 00:58:29,973
-I did.
-She picked one.

1542
00:58:30,039 --> 00:58:32,842
Who did she choose? Let's find out.

1543
00:58:32,909 --> 00:58:34,177
Show us!

1544
00:58:34,244 --> 00:58:38,181
These are the two chefs
deeply beloved by children,

1545
00:58:38,248 --> 00:58:40,483
the two chefs
who have been doing the best on the show!

1546
00:58:40,550 --> 00:58:43,419
Whose side did Tiffany take?

1547
00:58:43,486 --> 00:58:46,389
What's the result? Who won?

1548
00:58:46,923 --> 00:58:49,359
-Who did Tiffany choose?
-Who is it?

1549
00:58:49,425 --> 00:58:50,727
Who is it?

1550
00:58:51,361 --> 00:58:53,863
SON JONG-WON WINS

1551
00:58:54,230 --> 00:58:55,331
TIFFANY'S BREAKFAST AT TIFFANY'S WINS

1552
00:58:55,398 --> 00:58:56,432
It's Jong-won!

1553
00:58:56,900 --> 00:58:59,068
HE SURELY IS THE BEST
AT FINE DINING EXPERIENCES

1554
00:58:59,135 --> 00:59:00,670
She chose Jong-won.

1555
00:59:00,737 --> 00:59:01,771
He's in first place.

1556
00:59:01,838 --> 00:59:03,540
From the beginning,

1557
00:59:03,606 --> 00:59:06,042
<i>everything was separated nicely</i>
<i>in act one and two,</i>

1558
00:59:06,109 --> 00:59:09,312
<i>coming in with a great balance</i>
<i>according to the order.</i>

1559
00:59:09,379 --> 00:59:12,715
<i>He seemed to have used</i>
<i>a cinematic element in the meal.</i>

1560
00:59:12,782 --> 00:59:16,753
She's saying Chef Jong-won's meal
had better structure.

1561
00:59:16,819 --> 00:59:19,789
I was overwhelmed
by the taste from San Francisco.

1562
00:59:19,856 --> 00:59:20,957
SAN FRANCISCO WINS

1563
00:59:21,024 --> 00:59:24,494
Chef Jong-won is now
solely in first place!

1564
00:59:24,561 --> 00:59:25,828
CONGRATULATIONS

1565
00:59:26,729 --> 00:59:29,732
Jong-won is now in first place!

1566
00:59:29,799 --> 00:59:32,669
JONG-WON TAKES HIS FIFTH STAR

1567
00:59:32,735 --> 00:59:34,270
He has five stars!

1568
00:59:34,337 --> 00:59:38,241
<i>Let us begin the second round</i>
<i>with Tiffany's ingredients.</i>

1569
00:59:38,308 --> 00:59:40,109
The one who returned to <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>

1570
00:59:40,176 --> 00:59:42,845
Tiffany's husband's friend, Chef Edward,

1571
00:59:42,912 --> 00:59:44,380
versus the one who went crazy
for the show,

1572
00:59:44,447 --> 00:59:47,283
the bride-to-be, Chef Park Eun-yeong.

1573
00:59:47,350 --> 00:59:48,851
Chef Edward

1574
00:59:48,918 --> 00:59:51,154
hasn't done the 15-minute cook-off
on this show

1575
00:59:51,220 --> 00:59:52,388
for the last eight months.

1576
00:59:53,022 --> 00:59:54,657
INTENSE

1577
00:59:55,258 --> 00:59:56,526
HE TORE THE STUDIO APART BACK THEN

1578
00:59:56,593 --> 00:59:58,595
Whoa, what is that?

1579
00:59:58,661 --> 01:00:01,130
-It's been eight months?
-Eight months.

1580
01:00:01,197 --> 01:00:03,433
The chefs before this round

1581
01:00:03,499 --> 01:00:06,102
made 4 dishes in just 15 minutes,

1582
01:00:06,169 --> 01:00:10,106
so I can probably make one.

1583
01:00:10,173 --> 01:00:11,874
He must make one.

1584
01:00:11,941 --> 01:00:13,876
-You have to.
-He has to finish it.

1585
01:00:13,943 --> 01:00:16,045
You can't make half a dish.
It has to be one.

1586
01:00:16,112 --> 01:00:18,481
I hope you finish within 15 minutes.

1587
01:00:18,548 --> 01:00:20,850
-I received a tip from the green room.
-Did you?

1588
01:00:21,417 --> 01:00:24,220
-Chef Eun-yeong has changed a lot.
-She has.

1589
01:00:24,287 --> 01:00:26,556
"If you're away from the show
for six months,

1590
01:00:26,623 --> 01:00:29,058
you can't call yourself
a chef of this show."

1591
01:00:29,359 --> 01:00:30,660
A SHOCKING STATEMENT

1592
01:00:31,194 --> 01:00:32,795
ASTONISHED

1593
01:00:32,862 --> 01:00:34,097
What did you mean by this?

1594
01:00:34,664 --> 01:00:36,599
We invited him back
after such a long time.

1595
01:00:36,666 --> 01:00:38,334
She's now bullying people.

1596
01:00:38,401 --> 01:00:40,136
But can we call him a chef of this show?

1597
01:00:40,203 --> 01:00:41,904
In order to settle on this show,

1598
01:00:41,971 --> 01:00:43,339
I danced and did just about everything.

1599
01:00:43,706 --> 01:00:44,674
JUST ABOUT EVERYTHING

1600
01:00:44,741 --> 01:00:47,043
So if you've been away
for more than six months,

1601
01:00:47,110 --> 01:00:49,579
I believe you're now an outsider,
a guest chef.

1602
01:00:49,646 --> 01:00:51,881
A guest chef, not a cast chef.

1603
01:00:51,948 --> 01:00:55,485
-After six months, you're a guest chef.
-A guest chef.

1604
01:00:55,551 --> 01:00:57,987
-She's saying that she can't approve…
-That's tough.

1605
01:00:58,054 --> 01:01:00,723
…of Chef Edward as a member of the show.

1606
01:01:00,790 --> 01:01:03,726
Is that disappointing for you,
Chef Edward?

1607
01:01:04,227 --> 01:01:05,395
Yes, of course.

1608
01:01:05,461 --> 01:01:07,330
-How disappointing.
-You're awful.

1609
01:01:07,397 --> 01:01:08,831
-He's disappointed.
-I'm sad.

1610
01:01:08,898 --> 01:01:11,000
He started the show with us.

1611
01:01:11,067 --> 01:01:13,569
But were you always here with us
in your heart?

1612
01:01:13,636 --> 01:01:14,937
That's right.

1613
01:01:15,004 --> 01:01:17,240
You're always here. No, here.

1614
01:01:17,306 --> 01:01:19,976
<i>Chef & My Fridge</i> is in his heart.

1615
01:01:20,043 --> 01:01:22,478
You two are
about to fill the order titled,

1616
01:01:22,545 --> 01:01:24,080
-Fany Time.
-Fany Time.

1617
01:01:24,147 --> 01:01:25,948
It's about parties.

1618
01:01:26,015 --> 01:01:28,184
Chef Edward, do you often go to parties?

1619
01:01:28,251 --> 01:01:30,019
When I was younger, I partied…

1620
01:01:30,820 --> 01:01:31,954
every night.

1621
01:01:32,021 --> 01:01:33,990
-Every night.
-Every night.

1622
01:01:34,057 --> 01:01:35,224
It's a lot of fun.

1623
01:01:35,291 --> 01:01:36,626
PARTY MAN EDDIE

1624
01:01:36,693 --> 01:01:39,328
Chef Eun-yeong, do you go to parties?

1625
01:01:39,395 --> 01:01:41,497
I wouldn't call them parties.

1626
01:01:41,564 --> 01:01:42,799
-Banquets.
-Banquets.

1627
01:01:42,865 --> 01:01:44,100
-I'm more familiar with that.
-Banquets.

1628
01:01:44,167 --> 01:01:46,969
-Call me the Banquet Girl.
-Banquet Girl?

1629
01:01:47,036 --> 01:01:48,738
What's a Banquet Girl?

1630
01:01:48,805 --> 01:01:51,607
-I'll fight today as the Banquet Girl.
-Like banquet noodles.

1631
01:01:52,041 --> 01:01:54,010
CHEF EDWARD'S INGREDIENTS:
BREAD, COCONUT CREAM, CHAMPAGNE

1632
01:01:54,077 --> 01:01:56,612
HONEY, RASPBERRY JAM, CONDENSED MILK,
RICOTTA, LEMON, WATERMELON, AND MORE

1633
01:01:56,679 --> 01:01:58,981
What are you making, Chef Edward?

1634
01:01:59,048 --> 01:02:01,084
I'm making

1635
01:02:01,150 --> 01:02:05,221
Is Bibimbap Served at Weddings, Fany?

1636
01:02:05,988 --> 01:02:08,624
-Is Bibimbap Served at Weddings, Fany?
-Is Bibimbap Served at Weddings, Fany?

1637
01:02:08,691 --> 01:02:11,060
-Are you making bibimbap?
-Yes.

1638
01:02:11,461 --> 01:02:14,397
THE BIBIM MAN IS BACK!

1639
01:02:14,464 --> 01:02:18,101
When you're at a wedding,
there's always a wedding cake, right?

1640
01:02:18,167 --> 01:02:20,503
They're usually not that delicious.

1641
01:02:20,570 --> 01:02:23,039
So instead of a wedding cake,

1642
01:02:23,106 --> 01:02:25,975
I want to make a dessert bibimbap.

1643
01:02:26,042 --> 01:02:28,311
-Dessert bibimbap?
-Dessert bibimbap?

1644
01:02:28,377 --> 01:02:31,214
-Like the cake I once made?
-I'm scared.

1645
01:02:31,280 --> 01:02:34,650
-With fruit?
-Isn't bibimbap usually the main dish?

1646
01:02:34,717 --> 01:02:36,452
-Dessert bibimbap?
-Dessert bibimbap?

1647
01:02:36,519 --> 01:02:37,687
-Fruit bibimbap.
-Dessert.

1648
01:02:37,754 --> 01:02:38,855
-Fruit bibimbap.
-Fruit?

1649
01:02:38,921 --> 01:02:40,757
-Fruit bibimbap?
-Fruit bibimbap.

1650
01:02:40,823 --> 01:02:42,058
-Fruit bibimbap?
-Does this mean

1651
01:02:42,125 --> 01:02:43,626
you'll use fruit instead of veggies?

1652
01:02:43,693 --> 01:02:44,761
-Yes.
-That's new.

1653
01:02:45,228 --> 01:02:47,430
AMAZED

1654
01:02:47,497 --> 01:02:49,999
-That's amazing. I like these ideas.
-Will it taste good?

1655
01:02:50,566 --> 01:02:51,801
It's kind of like that.

1656
01:02:51,868 --> 01:02:53,202
Mango sticky rice.

1657
01:02:53,269 --> 01:02:56,205
Wouldn't that be considered
fruit bibimbap?

1658
01:02:56,272 --> 01:02:57,573
-Fruit?
-Fruit.

1659
01:02:57,640 --> 01:02:59,442
-What?
-But he's using gochujang.

1660
01:02:59,509 --> 01:03:00,610
-He is?
-Yes.

1661
01:03:00,676 --> 01:03:02,178
I should turn this on.

1662
01:03:02,245 --> 01:03:03,513
FRUIT AND GOCHUJANG?

1663
01:03:03,579 --> 01:03:05,815
Fruit, rice, and gochujang?

1664
01:03:05,882 --> 01:03:07,416
Was the flight a bit too long?

1665
01:03:07,683 --> 01:03:08,885
THE AFTERMATH OF A 15-HOUR FLIGHT

1666
01:03:08,951 --> 01:03:11,020
You crave gochujang
when you're on a flight.

1667
01:03:11,087 --> 01:03:14,090
It's completely unimaginable.

1668
01:03:14,157 --> 01:03:16,125
I agree. I feel…

1669
01:03:17,260 --> 01:03:18,961
I'll trust you.

1670
01:03:19,529 --> 01:03:21,597
CHEF EUN-YEONG'S INGREDIENTS:
TOFU, SCALLOP, SQUID, ALMOND MILK

1671
01:03:21,664 --> 01:03:23,966
SESAME DRESSING, LEMON JUICE,
BONELESS CHICKEN THIGHS, APPLE, AND MORE

1672
01:03:24,033 --> 01:03:27,270
Chef Eun-yeong will be fighting him today.
What are you making?

1673
01:03:27,336 --> 01:03:28,738
The name of my dish is

1674
01:03:28,805 --> 01:03:30,373
The Star Is Mine, Gee.

1675
01:03:30,439 --> 01:03:31,707
A-ha.

1676
01:03:32,375 --> 01:03:35,011
The most important thing
at a wedding is the food.

1677
01:03:35,077 --> 01:03:37,079
-Yes.
-And if you decide

1678
01:03:37,146 --> 01:03:40,416
to do a course meal with Chinese food,
it becomes quite expensive.

1679
01:03:40,483 --> 01:03:42,885
-Yes.
-That's a luxurious meal.

1680
01:03:42,952 --> 01:03:47,190
But I still wanted to congratulate
your marriage with Chinese food.

1681
01:03:47,256 --> 01:03:49,692
So I'm going to make dishes
that are served

1682
01:03:49,759 --> 01:03:51,727
-in Chinese banquets.
-Chinese banquets?

1683
01:03:51,794 --> 01:03:54,630
People often eat cream cake
when they celebrate, don't they?

1684
01:03:54,697 --> 01:03:57,800
But I'll add an eastern touch

1685
01:03:57,867 --> 01:04:01,337
and make a cake with meringue.

1686
01:04:01,404 --> 01:04:04,207
I'll serve it with a cold salad
that's always served at a Chinese banquet,

1687
01:04:04,273 --> 01:04:06,075
-so two dishes.
-A cold salad.

1688
01:04:06,142 --> 01:04:08,110
-That sounds good.
-All right.

1689
01:04:08,177 --> 01:04:11,447
Please ready the 15-minute timer.

1690
01:04:11,514 --> 01:04:14,083
Let us begin their battle now.

1691
01:04:14,150 --> 01:04:17,553
She's here to throw a huge feast
for the ladies who are now off the market,

1692
01:04:17,620 --> 01:04:20,156
the bride-to-be, Chef Park Eun-yeong!

1693
01:04:20,223 --> 01:04:22,892
He flew in all the way from America
to celebrate her marriage,

1694
01:04:22,959 --> 01:04:26,195
Tiffany's husband's friend,
Chef Edward Lee.

1695
01:04:27,430 --> 01:04:30,766
Which one of them will receive
the appreciation of the party girl?

1696
01:04:30,833 --> 01:04:32,969
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1697
01:04:35,137 --> 01:04:37,640
THE PARTY GUY RUNS TO THE COUNTER

1698
01:04:38,140 --> 01:04:41,010
-Wow.
-Husband's friend versus the bride-to-be.

1699
01:04:41,077 --> 01:04:42,678
How will he make the fruit bibimbap?

1700
01:04:42,745 --> 01:04:44,113
-He grabbed rice.
-There's rice.

1701
01:04:44,180 --> 01:04:45,481
-The rice?
-Right away?

1702
01:04:45,548 --> 01:04:46,682
Is he not using all of it?

1703
01:04:46,749 --> 01:04:49,151
He's putting it in water.

1704
01:04:49,218 --> 01:04:51,120
-I see. Without heating it?
-Why?

1705
01:04:51,187 --> 01:04:52,221
-It's porridge.
-It's porridge.

1706
01:04:52,288 --> 01:04:53,322
-Is it?
-How will he do it?

1707
01:04:53,956 --> 01:04:54,790
PORRIDGE…

1708
01:04:54,857 --> 01:04:56,359
-Huh? Bread?
-This time, bread.

1709
01:04:56,425 --> 01:04:58,661
-He's making circles.
-He cuts the bread in circles.

1710
01:04:59,295 --> 01:05:00,429
Can't imagine what he's making.

1711
01:05:00,496 --> 01:05:03,666
Chef Edward made a few rings.

1712
01:05:04,033 --> 01:05:06,035
THE BANQUET GIRL
FIGHTS BACK WITH MERINGUE!

1713
01:05:06,102 --> 01:05:08,304
Only egg whites?
Right. You're making meringue.

1714
01:05:08,371 --> 01:05:10,940
-Three? That'll be hard to do.
-Three is way too hard.

1715
01:05:11,007 --> 01:05:12,275
-It'll take over five minutes.
-At least five.

1716
01:05:12,341 --> 01:05:13,442
It'll take up five minutes.

1717
01:05:14,543 --> 01:05:15,478
A WHIPPING MACHINE

1718
01:05:15,544 --> 01:05:16,812
There was a machine.

1719
01:05:16,879 --> 01:05:19,749
They make good machines these days.

1720
01:05:19,815 --> 01:05:22,418
-She'll make cake with that.
-Wow.

1721
01:05:22,485 --> 01:05:23,953
How come it whips so quickly?

1722
01:05:24,020 --> 01:05:24,954
That's really fast.

1723
01:05:25,821 --> 01:05:27,356
That didn't take long.

1724
01:05:29,125 --> 01:05:33,930
REMEMBERING THE OLD DAYS
WHEN THEY WHIPPED TILL THEIR ARMS GAVE OUT

1725
01:05:35,064 --> 01:05:36,799
What have we been doing?

1726
01:05:37,400 --> 01:05:38,534
BACK TO THE PARTY!

1727
01:05:38,601 --> 01:05:42,004
-Chef Edward…
-Chef Edward is…

1728
01:05:42,071 --> 01:05:46,075
-That's a recipe Poong tried and failed.
-That's my pizza.

1729
01:05:46,142 --> 01:05:48,144
-But there's water.
-Kim Gil-li Pizza.

1730
01:05:48,210 --> 01:05:50,379
-He's using coconut cream.
-Coconut milk.

1731
01:05:50,446 --> 01:05:52,815
-Never mind. It's different.
-It's different from here.

1732
01:05:53,149 --> 01:05:54,817
RICE MIXED WITH WATER AND COCONUT CREAM?

1733
01:05:54,884 --> 01:05:57,420
-That's coconut cream.
-Coconut milk?

1734
01:05:57,486 --> 01:05:59,722
-I get it!
-That's how you make mango sticky rice.

1735
01:05:59,789 --> 01:06:00,790
-You're right.
-It's like that.

1736
01:06:00,856 --> 01:06:01,857
She mentioned it earlier.

1737
01:06:01,924 --> 01:06:04,927
That's how you make mango sticky rice.

1738
01:06:04,994 --> 01:06:06,395
There's a Korean version called <i>yaksik.</i>

1739
01:06:06,462 --> 01:06:07,830
-<i>Yaksik.</i>
-Yes.

1740
01:06:10,499 --> 01:06:11,667
She whipped it so quickly.

1741
01:06:11,734 --> 01:06:13,235
She's done making the meringue.

1742
01:06:13,302 --> 01:06:14,637
She's done with the meringue.

1743
01:06:14,704 --> 01:06:16,739
She made the meringue in just two minutes.

1744
01:06:16,806 --> 01:06:18,140
She's adding tofu.

1745
01:06:18,207 --> 01:06:19,875
-Tofu?
-What?

1746
01:06:19,942 --> 01:06:21,210
What did she do with the tofu?

1747
01:06:21,277 --> 01:06:24,113
-She mashed it with her hand.
-Just by hand?

1748
01:06:24,947 --> 01:06:26,682
THE PARTY GUY PICKS UP CHAMPAGNE

1749
01:06:27,516 --> 01:06:30,186
LIKE THE CHAMPAGNE TOWER
AT THE WEDDING RECEPTION!

1750
01:06:30,252 --> 01:06:31,420
Champagne!

1751
01:06:31,654 --> 01:06:32,621
THREE BOWLS OF CHAMPAGNE

1752
01:06:32,688 --> 01:06:33,656
Whoa, champagne!

1753
01:06:35,191 --> 01:06:37,126
CHAMPAGNE IN THE POT!

1754
01:06:37,193 --> 01:06:38,961
He's adding champagne.

1755
01:06:39,028 --> 01:06:41,197
That's honey. He's adding honey.

1756
01:06:41,263 --> 01:06:42,598
-How cute.
-Champagne and honey.

1757
01:06:42,665 --> 01:06:44,066
DRIPPING HONEY

1758
01:06:46,002 --> 01:06:48,871
-Champagne and honey?
-And in the rice too.

1759
01:06:48,938 --> 01:06:50,506
-Gochujang?
-What?

1760
01:06:50,773 --> 01:06:51,640
SURPRISED

1761
01:06:51,707 --> 01:06:54,877
-Champagne, honey, and gochujang.
-That's a unique mix.

1762
01:06:54,944 --> 01:06:57,213
There's this Mexican candy

1763
01:06:57,279 --> 01:07:01,484
made with mango and chili sprinkles.

1764
01:07:01,550 --> 01:07:04,854
The spiciness and sweetness

1765
01:07:04,920 --> 01:07:07,323
work together very nicely.

1766
01:07:07,390 --> 01:07:09,125
-Like mango and chili.
-Yes.

1767
01:07:09,191 --> 01:07:10,192
CHAMPAGNE GOCHUJANG

1768
01:07:10,259 --> 01:07:11,827
WHAT'S THE BANQUET GIRL DOING?

1769
01:07:11,894 --> 01:07:13,662
What's she doing with the plastic wrap?

1770
01:07:15,097 --> 01:07:17,967
She stacks two bowls
and puts plastic wrap on them.

1771
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:19,702
She's going to steam something.

1772
01:07:19,769 --> 01:07:23,372
Eun-yeong puts the meringue into the bowl.

1773
01:07:23,439 --> 01:07:25,841
It looks rather small.
Is that going to be a cake?

1774
01:07:25,908 --> 01:07:27,309
Yes, it's a mini cake.

1775
01:07:27,376 --> 01:07:29,078
She's steaming it.

1776
01:07:29,145 --> 01:07:31,981
-It'll turn out very soft.
-Really?

1777
01:07:33,682 --> 01:07:35,351
He's using the rings.

1778
01:07:36,952 --> 01:07:38,954
He's top-notch
when it comes to creativity.

1779
01:07:39,021 --> 01:07:43,125
He made ring shapes with bread.

1780
01:07:43,192 --> 01:07:45,127
They look like onion rings.

1781
01:07:45,194 --> 01:07:46,362
4. TOAST RINGS IN BUTTER

1782
01:07:46,929 --> 01:07:48,164
Sambal.

1783
01:07:48,230 --> 01:07:49,131
Sambal?

1784
01:07:49,198 --> 01:07:52,535
-No, it's strawberry… Raspberry jam.
-Strawberry jam?

1785
01:07:52,601 --> 01:07:56,038
I have lots of jams.
Fig jam, strawberry jam…

1786
01:07:56,105 --> 01:07:58,574
And he's using all of them
to make bibimbap.

1787
01:07:58,641 --> 01:08:00,176
It's hard to imagine.

1788
01:08:00,443 --> 01:08:01,410
5 MINUTES HAVE PASSED!

1789
01:08:01,477 --> 01:08:03,312
What's she using? Scallops?

1790
01:08:03,379 --> 01:08:05,014
-Scallops.
-Scallops?

1791
01:08:05,081 --> 01:08:05,915
WHAT'S NEXT?

1792
01:08:05,981 --> 01:08:07,183
Squid?

1793
01:08:07,950 --> 01:08:11,053
Chef Eun-yeong parboils
scallops and squid.

1794
01:08:11,120 --> 01:08:13,556
Those must be for the cold salad.

1795
01:08:13,622 --> 01:08:17,193
Yes, Chinese cold salads are often made
with parboiled ingredients.

1796
01:08:17,960 --> 01:08:19,595
NEXT, THE COLD SALAD SAUCE!

1797
01:08:19,995 --> 01:08:21,163
ALMOND MILK

1798
01:08:21,530 --> 01:08:22,731
SESAME DRESSING

1799
01:08:22,798 --> 01:08:24,100
What are you making now, Eun-yeong?

1800
01:08:24,166 --> 01:08:26,202
-I made the cold salad dressing.
-Salad dressing.

1801
01:08:26,268 --> 01:08:28,337
Sauce is everything.

1802
01:08:28,404 --> 01:08:31,040
-It's the most important.
-Yes, in Chinese cold salads.

1803
01:08:31,107 --> 01:08:33,476
-She puts it in the fridge.
-It didn't seem like the usual sauce.

1804
01:08:33,542 --> 01:08:34,877
No, it was different.

1805
01:08:34,944 --> 01:08:36,979
The color was a bit different.

1806
01:08:37,046 --> 01:08:38,614
She's using meat now.

1807
01:08:38,681 --> 01:08:39,782
-Is that pork?
-Banquet Girl.

1808
01:08:39,849 --> 01:08:40,916
-It's chicken.
-Chicken.

1809
01:08:40,983 --> 01:08:42,718
-Boneless thigh meat.
-Chicken thighs.

1810
01:08:42,785 --> 01:08:44,019
Chicken breast?

1811
01:08:45,454 --> 01:08:46,755
Prince's…

1812
01:08:46,822 --> 01:08:48,757
PRINCE AND PRINCESS'S CHICKEN!

1813
01:08:48,824 --> 01:08:51,760
-Bokja's food.
-The meat she cooks for her dogs,

1814
01:08:51,827 --> 01:08:53,162
chicken breast.

1815
01:08:53,229 --> 01:08:54,163
Chicken thighs.

1816
01:08:54,230 --> 01:08:55,498
-Thighs.
-Yes.

1817
01:08:55,564 --> 01:08:57,666
HE'S ALSO HAVING A TOUGH TIME HEARING

1818
01:08:59,001 --> 01:08:59,902
What's that?

1819
01:08:59,969 --> 01:09:01,570
-Condensed milk?
-Even condensed milk?

1820
01:09:01,637 --> 01:09:04,707
-It has everything that you like.
-Wouldn't it be too sweet?

1821
01:09:04,773 --> 01:09:06,108
But you know,

1822
01:09:06,175 --> 01:09:08,611
would I like it when they're together?

1823
01:09:09,044 --> 01:09:09,879
KOREAN CHEFS WOULDN'T DO THIS

1824
01:09:09,945 --> 01:09:12,481
It's a mix of ingredients
Korean chefs wouldn't try.

1825
01:09:12,748 --> 01:09:14,416
THAT'S EDWARD'S CHARM!

1826
01:09:14,483 --> 01:09:17,520
I wonder what Edward will make today.

1827
01:09:17,586 --> 01:09:20,389
We're seeing him here
for the first time in eight months.

1828
01:09:20,456 --> 01:09:22,158
-What's that?
-Ricotta.

1829
01:09:22,224 --> 01:09:24,093
Ricotta cheese.

1830
01:09:24,160 --> 01:09:25,094
It sounds good.

1831
01:09:25,161 --> 01:09:27,563
I usually eat that with my salad.

1832
01:09:27,630 --> 01:09:30,432
He's mixing her salad topping with rice!

1833
01:09:30,499 --> 01:09:33,469
The mix he has made
is something we can't even imagine.

1834
01:09:33,536 --> 01:09:34,937
-This is fun.
-We aren't sure yet.

1835
01:09:35,004 --> 01:09:37,540
It looks like sticky rice
after he added cheese.

1836
01:09:37,606 --> 01:09:39,308
LEMON ZEST

1837
01:09:39,375 --> 01:09:40,409
And lemon juice.

1838
01:09:40,476 --> 01:09:43,312
-That's a lot.
-That is quite a lot.

1839
01:09:43,379 --> 01:09:45,447
He added quite a lot.
It must be pretty sour.

1840
01:09:45,514 --> 01:09:47,750
-Ground pepper?
-Pepper will go well.

1841
01:09:47,816 --> 01:09:49,218
LEMON CHEESE RICE

1842
01:09:49,285 --> 01:09:50,319
Use ground pepper wisely.

1843
01:09:50,386 --> 01:09:51,353
Don't make it too spicy.

1844
01:09:51,420 --> 01:09:53,789
He lost the previous round
because of the ground pepper.

1845
01:09:53,856 --> 01:09:55,457
-Six minutes, forty seconds.
-Chilling it.

1846
01:09:55,524 --> 01:09:57,293
-That's not a lot of time.
-He's chilling it.

1847
01:09:58,827 --> 01:10:00,829
Eun-yeong uses an apple.

1848
01:10:01,096 --> 01:10:02,865
APPLE

1849
01:10:03,666 --> 01:10:05,601
SLICED THINLY LIKE CHIPS

1850
01:10:05,668 --> 01:10:07,236
Celery.

1851
01:10:07,303 --> 01:10:10,906
-Eun-yeong is moving very fast.
-She peeled it slightly.

1852
01:10:10,973 --> 01:10:14,343
What's that? Watermelon.

1853
01:10:14,410 --> 01:10:18,013
Edward chops watermelon into tiny pieces.

1854
01:10:18,080 --> 01:10:20,249
He's become much faster too.

1855
01:10:20,316 --> 01:10:21,951
-What's that?
-What is that?

1856
01:10:22,017 --> 01:10:23,586
-Mint.
-Mint?

1857
01:10:23,652 --> 01:10:26,255
-Six minutes left.
-Watermelon and mint.

1858
01:10:26,322 --> 01:10:27,790
Persimmon.

1859
01:10:27,856 --> 01:10:29,358
FRUIT BIBIMBAP TOPPING 2: PERSIMMON

1860
01:10:29,558 --> 01:10:30,392
ROUND CUTTER

1861
01:10:31,860 --> 01:10:35,397
Edward makes tiny
and round persimmon slices.

1862
01:10:35,464 --> 01:10:36,999
-Coin-shaped.
-Yes.

1863
01:10:37,066 --> 01:10:38,867
He still has his game.

1864
01:10:39,568 --> 01:10:41,203
A bit of soy sauce.

1865
01:10:41,670 --> 01:10:42,504
EGG YOLK

1866
01:10:43,405 --> 01:10:44,740
THE BANQUET GIRL MARINATES CHICKEN!

1867
01:10:44,807 --> 01:10:45,641
STARCH

1868
01:10:46,709 --> 01:10:47,776
STARCH WATER

1869
01:10:47,843 --> 01:10:49,144
MIXING

1870
01:10:49,378 --> 01:10:50,946
MIXING WHILE CHECKING THE MERINGUE

1871
01:10:51,013 --> 01:10:52,348
It's ready.

1872
01:10:52,414 --> 01:10:54,083
-The meringue.
-Can you see it?

1873
01:10:54,149 --> 01:10:56,051
-It didn't deflate.
-Does it look like cake?

1874
01:10:56,118 --> 01:10:58,120
-She's deep-frying the chicken.
-I see.

1875
01:10:58,187 --> 01:10:59,421
She's deep-frying those.

1876
01:10:59,488 --> 01:11:02,658
It looks really hot. Extremely hot.

1877
01:11:03,392 --> 01:11:04,960
Five minutes.

1878
01:11:05,027 --> 01:11:08,631
Five minutes left. Jung-hwan and Sung-jun!

1879
01:11:08,697 --> 01:11:10,566
-Please do the interim check.
-Okay.

1880
01:11:10,633 --> 01:11:11,634
Five minutes!

1881
01:11:11,700 --> 01:11:15,337
Will he return home with a star
after eight months of hiatus?

1882
01:11:15,404 --> 01:11:18,507
One side prepares for a party,
while the other cooks for a banquet.

1883
01:11:18,574 --> 01:11:19,708
That's right.

1884
01:11:19,775 --> 01:11:23,545
-Hard to imagine gochujang with fruit.
-It's hard to imagine.

1885
01:11:23,612 --> 01:11:25,047
What's this sauce?

1886
01:11:27,449 --> 01:11:30,185
-Try it. He cooked gochujang in champagne.
-Should I?

1887
01:11:30,252 --> 01:11:31,353
-I'm curious!
-I found this…

1888
01:11:31,420 --> 01:11:32,621
-It looks good.
-…so intriguing.

1889
01:11:32,688 --> 01:11:34,790
Has he created a harmonious flavor?

1890
01:11:34,857 --> 01:11:37,293
Try it, Chef Sung-jun.

1891
01:11:37,359 --> 01:11:38,961
-What's it like?
-What's the mix like?

1892
01:11:39,028 --> 01:11:40,729
What's it like?

1893
01:11:40,796 --> 01:11:42,197
-What's it like?
-What's the mix like?

1894
01:11:42,264 --> 01:11:43,432
NODS

1895
01:11:43,732 --> 01:11:45,467
It's good.

1896
01:11:45,534 --> 01:11:47,136
-It is?
-What's it like?

1897
01:11:47,202 --> 01:11:49,238
The spiciness adds a kick

1898
01:11:49,305 --> 01:11:51,307
and will balance out the greasiness.

1899
01:11:52,041 --> 01:11:53,008
Not so bad.

1900
01:11:53,075 --> 01:11:56,045
-Really?
-No one is as good as mixing as Edward is.

1901
01:11:56,111 --> 01:11:59,114
-He mixed gochujang, champagne…
-Raspberry.

1902
01:11:59,181 --> 01:12:02,217
…and raspberry jam,
which is hard for us to imagine.

1903
01:12:03,852 --> 01:12:05,854
WHAT ABOUT FRIED CHICKEN FOR THE BANQUET?

1904
01:12:06,055 --> 01:12:07,923
ADD CELERY!

1905
01:12:08,824 --> 01:12:13,362
7. DOUBLE-FRY BONELESS THIGHS,
SLIGHTLY FRY CELERY

1906
01:12:15,431 --> 01:12:17,166
Is that a green onion or a leek?

1907
01:12:17,533 --> 01:12:19,134
GREEN ONION

1908
01:12:19,835 --> 01:12:21,337
GARLIC

1909
01:12:21,904 --> 01:12:25,607
8. STIR-FRY GREEN ONION AND GARLIC
IN SOY SAUCE

1910
01:12:26,508 --> 01:12:28,344
Let's move on to the banquet.

1911
01:12:28,410 --> 01:12:30,312
-The banquet.
-What's going on here?

1912
01:12:30,379 --> 01:12:33,082
I'm working on the meringue…

1913
01:12:33,148 --> 01:12:36,185
It has deflated a little. Hasn't it?

1914
01:12:36,251 --> 01:12:38,487
-You can't help it. It happens.
-Right?

1915
01:12:38,554 --> 01:12:39,922
I see. So it does.

1916
01:12:39,988 --> 01:12:42,191
-Is there anything I can try?
-Nothing yet.

1917
01:12:42,257 --> 01:12:43,425
-Huh?
-Come on.

1918
01:12:44,126 --> 01:12:45,894
-This banquet…
-Doesn't have much food.

1919
01:12:46,362 --> 01:12:47,596
ALL HYPE, NO FOOD

1920
01:12:47,663 --> 01:12:48,897
-All the hype.
-He came to eat.

1921
01:12:48,964 --> 01:12:50,999
-She's using this.
-What's that?

1922
01:12:51,066 --> 01:12:52,368
-This!
-<i>Dogani-tang?</i>

1923
01:12:52,434 --> 01:12:53,969
It's Tiffany's ox knee soup.

1924
01:12:54,036 --> 01:12:55,104
I LIKE THAT

1925
01:12:55,170 --> 01:12:56,705
She's using the soup.

1926
01:12:56,772 --> 01:12:59,108
-She caught my attention.
-All this hype.

1927
01:12:59,174 --> 01:13:02,244
Chinese banquets always serve chicken.

1928
01:13:02,311 --> 01:13:05,914
-Is it like <i>gungbogyejeong?</i>
-It is.

1929
01:13:05,981 --> 01:13:07,349
GUNG… WHAT?

1930
01:13:09,184 --> 01:13:10,519
That sounds good.

1931
01:13:10,586 --> 01:13:13,489
She's cooking for a banquet,
but there's nothing for us to try.

1932
01:13:13,555 --> 01:13:16,125
-Three minutes left.
-Three minutes!

1933
01:13:16,191 --> 01:13:18,293
Eun-yeong is stir-frying chicken.

1934
01:13:18,360 --> 01:13:20,596
FRUIT BIBIMBAP TOPPING 4: APPLE

1935
01:13:20,662 --> 01:13:22,664
FRUIT BIBIMBAP TOPPING 5: STRAWBERRY

1936
01:13:23,332 --> 01:13:24,900
JULIENNED APPLE, STRAWBERRY SLICES

1937
01:13:25,434 --> 01:13:28,036
ALL DROPPED INTO
THE CHAMPAGNE AND LEMON JUICE MIX!

1938
01:13:28,470 --> 01:13:30,406
AND HE BEGINS TO PLATE THE DISH

1939
01:13:30,672 --> 01:13:33,342
AGAIN, THE CHAMPAGNE GOCHUJANG!

1940
01:13:33,409 --> 01:13:35,611
What on earth will that be like?

1941
01:13:35,677 --> 01:13:37,413
-What's he making?
-Once again,

1942
01:13:37,479 --> 01:13:39,314
-back to the party.
-What is that?

1943
01:13:39,381 --> 01:13:41,216
Edward begins to plate the dish.

1944
01:13:41,550 --> 01:13:42,751
SCARED YET CURIOUS OF THE SAUCE

1945
01:13:42,818 --> 01:13:46,288
You know how the greens go on top
in a stone pot to make bibimbap, right?

1946
01:13:46,355 --> 01:13:48,490
I think he's making that shape.
Is that right?

1947
01:13:48,557 --> 01:13:49,658
That's a unique shape.

1948
01:13:49,725 --> 01:13:50,993
-Is that right?
-It is.

1949
01:13:51,059 --> 01:13:52,528
-It is.
-It is.

1950
01:13:52,594 --> 01:13:54,129
I see. Your hair looks nice.

1951
01:13:55,731 --> 01:13:57,833
You look like a lion from this distance.

1952
01:13:57,900 --> 01:14:01,470
-He's roaring over here.
-He reminds me of a lion.

1953
01:14:01,537 --> 01:14:03,172
Bibimbap has vegetables neatly laid out.

1954
01:14:03,238 --> 01:14:05,107
Will she mix everything before eating it?

1955
01:14:05,174 --> 01:14:06,108
Really?

1956
01:14:06,175 --> 01:14:07,876
You have a minute and 40 seconds left.

1957
01:14:07,943 --> 01:14:09,812
She hasn't finished the cold salad yet.

1958
01:14:09,878 --> 01:14:12,714
-She's torching the seafood.
-To add a smoky flavor?

1959
01:14:12,781 --> 01:14:14,716
What's the dish called again?

1960
01:14:14,783 --> 01:14:16,018
The Star Is Mine, Gee.

1961
01:14:16,084 --> 01:14:17,252
HOP, HOP

1962
01:14:17,319 --> 01:14:18,320
You're moving your legs.

1963
01:14:18,520 --> 01:14:19,822
CAN'T SKIP THE PERFORMANCE

1964
01:14:20,022 --> 01:14:21,089
ALL RIGHT!

1965
01:14:21,356 --> 01:14:22,558
I am…

1966
01:14:23,559 --> 01:14:24,893
greatly inspired by this.

1967
01:14:24,960 --> 01:14:26,395
-I see.
-Are you sure?

1968
01:14:27,029 --> 01:14:28,397
There's not enough time.

1969
01:14:28,464 --> 01:14:32,201
We always wonder
how we should boil down the same note.

1970
01:14:32,267 --> 01:14:35,637
-How should we boil it down?
-How should you use your talent?

1971
01:14:35,704 --> 01:14:38,207
After all, it's the same dance move
and the same song.

1972
01:14:38,273 --> 01:14:40,209
She's saying harmony is important.

1973
01:14:40,275 --> 01:14:44,046
11. TOP SEAFOOD AND APPLE
WITH SAUCE, LEMON ZEST, AND SESAME OIL

1974
01:14:45,447 --> 01:14:47,916
THE PARTY GUY GRABS THE CHAMPAGNE AGAIN

1975
01:14:47,983 --> 01:14:50,219
-Fruit… This is new.
-It looks glamorous.

1976
01:14:50,285 --> 01:14:53,255
And blueberries.
He mixed watermelon with mint, right?

1977
01:14:53,322 --> 01:14:54,556
The rice is in the fridge.

1978
01:14:54,623 --> 01:14:56,625
-He's trying to make bibimbap.
-Look at that.

1979
01:14:56,692 --> 01:15:00,262
-The leftover?
-It's the rice and… What else?

1980
01:15:00,329 --> 01:15:03,365
-Rice, coconut milk, honey…
-Honey.

1981
01:15:03,432 --> 01:15:04,766
-Condensed milk.
-Condensed milk.

1982
01:15:04,833 --> 01:15:06,168
There's only a minute left.

1983
01:15:06,235 --> 01:15:07,336
UGH…

1984
01:15:07,402 --> 01:15:09,471
-Sung-jun.
-You have a minute left!

1985
01:15:09,538 --> 01:15:11,106
CAUTIOUS

1986
01:15:11,173 --> 01:15:14,376
Which chef do you think will win?
Does it taste okay?

1987
01:15:14,443 --> 01:15:16,044
HALF-WORRIED

1988
01:15:16,111 --> 01:15:17,412
HALF-EXCITED

1989
01:15:17,479 --> 01:15:18,313
LIP-SMACK

1990
01:15:18,680 --> 01:15:20,482
-Hmm?
-Does it taste okay?

1991
01:15:21,016 --> 01:15:22,217
It must be good.

1992
01:15:22,284 --> 01:15:23,552
It's a party.

1993
01:15:23,619 --> 01:15:24,620
-It is?
-It's a party.

1994
01:15:24,686 --> 01:15:25,521
-Whoa.
-A party.

1995
01:15:25,587 --> 01:15:27,789
You can taste
many different flavors in your mouth.

1996
01:15:27,856 --> 01:15:30,192
It feels like a party inside.

1997
01:15:30,259 --> 01:15:32,261
-Does anything hit you?
-It's nice.

1998
01:15:32,327 --> 01:15:33,428
It pops in the mouth.

1999
01:15:33,495 --> 01:15:34,930
Is he doing it right?

2000
01:15:34,997 --> 01:15:36,665
Your review was way too serious.

2001
01:15:36,732 --> 01:15:37,733
Exactly.

2002
01:15:37,799 --> 01:15:40,269
-Make it more exciting, like a party.
-Let's ban Sung-jun from doing this.

2003
01:15:40,335 --> 01:15:42,337
-"It's a party!"
-Sung-jun can't do this.

2004
01:15:42,404 --> 01:15:44,273
-It was so disappointing.
-You made no effort.

2005
01:15:44,339 --> 01:15:46,208
Nam-no was much better.

2006
01:15:46,275 --> 01:15:47,309
KICK HIM OUT!

2007
01:15:47,376 --> 01:15:49,211
-There's no excitement.
-Jung-hwan.

2008
01:15:49,278 --> 01:15:51,280
-He laughed at me too.
-Make sure you do it right.

2009
01:15:51,346 --> 01:15:53,382
-Let me give it a taste.
-Please do!

2010
01:15:53,448 --> 01:15:54,983
-Hot!
-See how he does it.

2011
01:15:55,050 --> 01:15:56,318
-It's good.
-It was too calm.

2012
01:15:56,385 --> 01:15:58,453
-What's it like?
-Jung-hwan!

2013
01:15:58,520 --> 01:16:02,824
Is it party time?

2014
01:16:02,891 --> 01:16:03,892
It's a crazy night!

2015
01:16:05,460 --> 01:16:06,795
SCREAM!

2016
01:16:07,596 --> 01:16:10,232
GEE, THIS IS IT!

2017
01:16:10,299 --> 01:16:11,533
It's a crazy night!

2018
01:16:11,600 --> 01:16:14,603
CRAZY PARTY IN THE STUDIO!

2019
01:16:14,670 --> 01:16:16,338
-That's what I'm talking about!
-Yes!

2020
01:16:16,405 --> 01:16:18,607
-It's a party.
-It is?

2021
01:16:18,674 --> 01:16:19,541
It's a party.

2022
01:16:20,242 --> 01:16:22,778
LEMON AND CHEESE RICE, IN!

2023
01:16:23,211 --> 01:16:24,046
ALMOND POWDER

2024
01:16:25,113 --> 01:16:27,983
MORE CHAMPAGNE IN CHAMPAGNE GOCHUJANG

2025
01:16:28,317 --> 01:16:30,085
THINNED OUT CHAMPAGNE GOCHUJANG

2026
01:16:30,352 --> 01:16:32,654
AS THE DRESSING!

2027
01:16:34,656 --> 01:16:35,691
THE BANQUET FEAST IS READY TOO!

2028
01:16:36,491 --> 01:16:38,493
KUNG PAO CHICKEN IS DONE

2029
01:16:38,560 --> 01:16:40,462
Ten. Nine.

2030
01:16:40,529 --> 01:16:42,364
-Eight. Seven.
-Eight. Seven.

2031
01:16:42,431 --> 01:16:44,032
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

2032
01:16:44,099 --> 01:16:47,102
A MINI CAKE WITH MERINGUE

2033
01:16:47,603 --> 01:16:50,772
FRUIT BIBIMBAP TOPPED WITH APPLE MINT

2034
01:16:51,206 --> 01:16:52,207
-One!
-One!

2035
01:16:52,274 --> 01:16:54,476
-Please ring the bell.
-Eun-yeong finishes first.

2036
01:16:54,543 --> 01:16:56,678
-Ring the bell.
-Ring it.

2037
01:16:56,745 --> 01:16:59,214
Edward finishes too.

2038
01:16:59,281 --> 01:17:00,849
A VERY INSPIRING BATTLE

2039
01:17:00,916 --> 01:17:02,451
The 15-minute cook-off is over.

2040
01:17:02,517 --> 01:17:04,052
A HUGE BANQUET, A BIG PARTY!

2041
01:17:04,119 --> 01:17:05,320
That's so pretty.

2042
01:17:06,021 --> 01:17:08,190
My gosh. It's so pretty.

2043
01:17:08,256 --> 01:17:09,324
-It's so pretty.
-It is.

2044
01:17:09,391 --> 01:17:11,193
-It's pretty.
-It really is.

2045
01:17:11,259 --> 01:17:16,164
Both dishes were finished for Tiffany.

2046
01:17:16,231 --> 01:17:20,869
First, please try Chef Eun-yeong's dish,
The Star Is Mine, Gee.

2047
01:17:21,570 --> 01:17:24,439
A CHINESE-STYLE BANQUET MEAL

2048
01:17:25,807 --> 01:17:28,844
CHICKEN CAKE?

2049
01:17:28,910 --> 01:17:31,213
AND COLD SALAD TO STIMULATE YOUR APPETITE

2050
01:17:32,314 --> 01:17:35,083
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
THE STAR IS MINE, GEE

2051
01:17:35,817 --> 01:17:39,021
One of them is a cake.

2052
01:17:39,087 --> 01:17:41,523
-Try the cold salad first.
-The cold salad.

2053
01:17:41,590 --> 01:17:43,892
-That's how it is in Chinese cuisine.
-Cold salad first.

2054
01:17:44,593 --> 01:17:45,927
-I'm excited.
-Sure.

2055
01:17:46,928 --> 01:17:47,863
Chinese cold salad.

2056
01:17:50,966 --> 01:17:52,501
FOCUSED

2057
01:17:52,567 --> 01:17:54,202
MMM

2058
01:17:54,269 --> 01:17:56,371
NODDING SILENTLY

2059
01:17:56,438 --> 01:17:58,440
Scallops and apples go well together.

2060
01:17:59,474 --> 01:18:01,176
It tastes like a wedding.

2061
01:18:01,243 --> 01:18:04,379
-Does it really?
-Yes.

2062
01:18:04,446 --> 01:18:07,749
It tastes refreshing, pure,

2063
01:18:07,816 --> 01:18:11,887
-clean, with a bit of sourness.
-The cold salad.

2064
01:18:11,953 --> 01:18:15,290
It's a cold salad suitable for a wedding.

2065
01:18:15,357 --> 01:18:17,726
Like the bride in white. Refreshing.

2066
01:18:17,793 --> 01:18:18,627
It's intriguing.

2067
01:18:18,694 --> 01:18:20,395
Let me have a little more.

2068
01:18:20,462 --> 01:18:21,830
She says it tastes like a wedding.

2069
01:18:23,632 --> 01:18:24,733
MMM

2070
01:18:24,800 --> 01:18:27,669
-Does it stimulate your appetite?
-Yes.

2071
01:18:27,736 --> 01:18:31,139
This dish alone
already makes me feel good.

2072
01:18:31,873 --> 01:18:34,076
Yes, you should feel good when you eat.

2073
01:18:34,142 --> 01:18:36,278
-This is the main dish.
-The cake.

2074
01:18:36,344 --> 01:18:37,479
Chicken cake?

2075
01:18:37,546 --> 01:18:39,081
Is this how you eat cake in China?

2076
01:18:39,147 --> 01:18:41,416
-No.
-Do they have cakes like this?

2077
01:18:41,483 --> 01:18:43,585
-She says no.
-It's Kung Pao chicken.

2078
01:18:43,652 --> 01:18:46,121
There's a famous dish
called Kung Pao chicken in China.

2079
01:18:46,188 --> 01:18:48,690
I made that,
and topped it with a steamed meringue.

2080
01:18:48,757 --> 01:18:51,259
It's a chicken dish
made with diced ingredients,

2081
01:18:51,326 --> 01:18:54,629
and it sometimes has peanuts in it too.

2082
01:18:54,696 --> 01:18:56,031
The Chinese cuisine expert.

2083
01:18:56,098 --> 01:18:58,166
And she just made a cake shape
with meringue, right?

2084
01:18:58,233 --> 01:18:59,735
-If you use meringue, it's a cake.
-Cake.

2085
01:18:59,801 --> 01:19:02,804
According to Amy Park, that is so.

2086
01:19:03,338 --> 01:19:06,274
SHE FINALLY TRIES THE CHINESE CAKE

2087
01:19:08,343 --> 01:19:09,878
SO?

2088
01:19:12,214 --> 01:19:13,215
MMM

2089
01:19:13,281 --> 01:19:14,916
I think I see a smile on you.

2090
01:19:14,983 --> 01:19:17,986
You suddenly looked so happy
as soon as you ate that.

2091
01:19:18,887 --> 01:19:21,690
It's so tender.

2092
01:19:21,757 --> 01:19:24,392
I also love how she used
<i>dogani-tang,</i> ox knee soup.

2093
01:19:24,459 --> 01:19:26,194
-She used the broth.
-Yes, it feels…

2094
01:19:26,261 --> 01:19:28,130
<i>Yes, she used that broth.</i>

2095
01:19:28,196 --> 01:19:29,698
Does your cartilage feel better?

2096
01:19:29,765 --> 01:19:31,733
Yes, I feel like
my joints are getting better.

2097
01:19:33,068 --> 01:19:36,238
-I love the texture of the meringue.
-Is that so?

2098
01:19:36,304 --> 01:19:39,407
It feels both like eggs and pudding.

2099
01:19:40,175 --> 01:19:41,476
It was worth the effort.

2100
01:19:41,543 --> 01:19:43,211
It feels like

2101
01:19:43,278 --> 01:19:45,714
there's a fun party in my mouth.

2102
01:19:45,781 --> 01:19:48,817
-It does feel like a banquet.
-A banquet.

2103
01:19:48,884 --> 01:19:50,485
What's the sauce like?

2104
01:19:50,552 --> 01:19:52,821
When most people
think of Kung Pao chicken,

2105
01:19:52,888 --> 01:19:55,590
<i>they think of something sweet and sour.</i>

2106
01:19:55,657 --> 01:19:57,793
But this one tastes a bit smoky.

2107
01:19:57,859 --> 01:19:59,561
-It's a bit… Yes.
-Smoky?

2108
01:19:59,628 --> 01:20:01,129
Was it intentional?

2109
01:20:01,196 --> 01:20:02,898
-The smoky flavor?
-Yes.

2110
01:20:02,964 --> 01:20:04,299
She must've burnt something.

2111
01:20:04,366 --> 01:20:05,333
A BIT FLUSTERED

2112
01:20:05,400 --> 01:20:08,837
It wasn't intentional,
but I get why she can feel that way.

2113
01:20:08,904 --> 01:20:10,472
-She's stuttering.
-I coated the chicken

2114
01:20:10,539 --> 01:20:14,042
in soy sauce before I deep-fried it,
so it could feel that way.

2115
01:20:14,109 --> 01:20:16,444
-In soy sauce.
-And over high heat, right?

2116
01:20:17,179 --> 01:20:18,113
CONVINCED, KEEPS EATING

2117
01:20:18,180 --> 01:20:20,081
She suddenly looks very happy.

2118
01:20:20,782 --> 01:20:23,685
It's really tender,
thanks to the bone soup.

2119
01:20:23,752 --> 01:20:25,587
It feels like food

2120
01:20:25,654 --> 01:20:27,889
-for a wedding reception.
-Wedding food?

2121
01:20:27,956 --> 01:20:30,192
Dishes for the wedding guests.

2122
01:20:30,258 --> 01:20:32,761
I see. She managed to fill the order.

2123
01:20:32,828 --> 01:20:35,630
Will you serve something like this
at your wedding?

2124
01:20:35,697 --> 01:20:37,399
I'm going with Western cuisine.

2125
01:20:37,465 --> 01:20:40,202
-Because you're Amy?
-Chinese food is expensive.

2126
01:20:40,268 --> 01:20:42,003
-It's expensive.
-Yes, she said that.

2127
01:20:42,070 --> 01:20:44,339
-That's why you can't do it.
-It's quite expensive.

2128
01:20:44,406 --> 01:20:45,740
Next,

2129
01:20:45,807 --> 01:20:49,678
please try Chef Edward's dish,
Is Bibimbap Served at Weddings, Fany?

2130
01:20:51,913 --> 01:20:57,552
FRUIT BIBIMBAP
ENJOYED WITH GOCHUJANG SAUCE

2131
01:21:01,790 --> 01:21:04,693
CHEF EDWARD LEE'S
IS BIBIMBAP SERVED AT WEDDINGS, FANY?

2132
01:21:05,260 --> 01:21:07,429
How should I eat this?

2133
01:21:07,495 --> 01:21:10,332
-Edward?
-One moment, please.

2134
01:21:10,398 --> 01:21:11,766
He prepared something.

2135
01:21:11,833 --> 01:21:13,668
-He'll do something.
-He always does that.

2136
01:21:13,735 --> 01:21:15,170
He's good at that.

2137
01:21:15,470 --> 01:21:17,005
AMAZED

2138
01:21:17,372 --> 01:21:19,808
WEDDING CANDLES

2139
01:21:20,742 --> 01:21:22,043
Yes.

2140
01:21:22,110 --> 01:21:23,912
-How beautiful!
-This is a nice surprise!

2141
01:21:24,412 --> 01:21:25,547
BUT THEY HAVE NO HEADS

2142
01:21:25,614 --> 01:21:28,116
-The neck…
-No heads. Only the neck and below.

2143
01:21:28,183 --> 01:21:30,018
He's your husband's friend.

2144
01:21:30,085 --> 01:21:33,688
You two haven't done the wedding yet.

2145
01:21:33,755 --> 01:21:36,491
-Are you doing this for Yo-han too?
-Yes.

2146
01:21:36,558 --> 01:21:37,726
-I see.
-Thank you.

2147
01:21:37,792 --> 01:21:39,060
I wish you a long and happy married life.

2148
01:21:39,127 --> 01:21:40,862
Thank you.

2149
01:21:40,929 --> 01:21:42,097
As for the fruit bibimbap,

2150
01:21:42,163 --> 01:21:46,434
pick out a piece of fruit
and grab some lemon cheese rice.

2151
01:21:46,501 --> 01:21:47,903
-Then, enjoy.
-Okay.

2152
01:21:47,969 --> 01:21:49,204
With the lemon cheese rice.

2153
01:21:49,271 --> 01:21:52,674
He poured the gochujang sauce
over the strawberries.

2154
01:21:52,741 --> 01:21:54,376
<i>He did.</i>

2155
01:21:54,442 --> 01:21:59,014
This is not the bibimbap
we're familiar with.

2156
01:21:59,080 --> 01:22:00,849
-I chose watermelon.
-Now, look.

2157
01:22:00,916 --> 01:22:03,151
-There's rice with the watermelon.
-Yes.

2158
01:22:03,218 --> 01:22:05,220
CAUTIOUSLY TAKES A BITE

2159
01:22:07,789 --> 01:22:09,291
Rice and fruit.

2160
01:22:10,992 --> 01:22:11,826
WIDE-EYED

2161
01:22:11,893 --> 01:22:14,696
How are we supposed to process this?

2162
01:22:14,763 --> 01:22:16,998
-The edges are bread, right?
-Yes.

2163
01:22:17,065 --> 01:22:20,902
-I'll cut it.
-Try the bread, cheese rice, and fruit.

2164
01:22:20,969 --> 01:22:24,306
Let me try a piece of strawberry
with lots of gochujang sauce on it.

2165
01:22:24,372 --> 01:22:26,841
She said she always dipped those
in condensed milk.

2166
01:22:26,908 --> 01:22:28,510
<i>It's now covered with gochujang.</i>

2167
01:22:28,576 --> 01:22:29,711
DUNKED IN GOCHUJANG SAUCE

2168
01:22:29,778 --> 01:22:32,580
If this is good,
she can eat it with gochujang from now on.

2169
01:22:32,647 --> 01:22:33,715
So?

2170
01:22:33,782 --> 01:22:36,051
It's hard to imagine what this is like.

2171
01:22:36,117 --> 01:22:39,020
My first question is this.
Does it taste like gochujang?

2172
01:22:39,087 --> 01:22:42,324
-Can you taste it?
-She's a bit surprised.

2173
01:22:42,390 --> 01:22:46,161
I see. I hope Edward's intention
comes across accurately.

2174
01:22:46,227 --> 01:22:49,264
-It doesn't taste like gochujang.
-No?

2175
01:22:49,331 --> 01:22:50,565
-But he used it.
-It's like…

2176
01:22:50,632 --> 01:22:53,335
What's the powder on top?

2177
01:22:53,401 --> 01:22:55,403
-Nuts.
-This powder

2178
01:22:55,470 --> 01:22:59,541
adds a bit of weight
to the light and refreshing fruit flavors.

2179
01:22:59,607 --> 01:23:03,578
-I see.
-The powder holds the fruits back

2180
01:23:03,645 --> 01:23:06,715
and brings them together as one,
so to say.

2181
01:23:08,283 --> 01:23:09,617
It's fascinating.

2182
01:23:09,684 --> 01:23:10,852
A fascinating flavor.

2183
01:23:12,420 --> 01:23:13,788
NEXT, WITH PERSIMMON

2184
01:23:13,855 --> 01:23:16,224
-Persimmon.
-That's persimmon.

2185
01:23:16,491 --> 01:23:18,193
TAKING A BITE WITH TRUST

2186
01:23:18,259 --> 01:23:21,262
A new dish by the man of mixed culture,
fruit bibimbap.

2187
01:23:21,329 --> 01:23:22,397
THE FROWN OF ACKNOWLEDGEMENT

2188
01:23:22,464 --> 01:23:26,935
<i>I expected the flavors to be more simple.</i>

2189
01:23:27,002 --> 01:23:30,972
But they mix and clash in a colorful way.

2190
01:23:31,539 --> 01:23:33,441
It's really fascinating.

2191
01:23:33,508 --> 01:23:35,543
It's still hard to imagine
even with the explanation.

2192
01:23:35,610 --> 01:23:37,078
Right? I can't.

2193
01:23:37,145 --> 01:23:38,480
We'll have to try it to know.

2194
01:23:39,748 --> 01:23:42,117
I can't stop eating it.

2195
01:23:42,183 --> 01:23:43,818
-Is the rice good too?
-Yes.

2196
01:23:44,319 --> 01:23:45,987
Yes, rice is the best remedy.

2197
01:23:46,054 --> 01:23:47,756
-Will you try it, Hyo-yeon?
-May I?

2198
01:23:47,822 --> 01:23:49,858
-Like you're a wedding guest.
-Okay.

2199
01:23:49,924 --> 01:23:51,826
-This is the banquet, right?
-Yes.

2200
01:23:52,193 --> 01:23:53,962
THE BANQUET GIRL'S PERSONAL CREATION

2201
01:23:54,029 --> 01:23:56,097
-Apple and squid?
-Yes.

2202
01:23:56,164 --> 01:23:57,899
-And a scallop.
-A scallop.

2203
01:23:58,299 --> 01:23:59,934
HOW IS IT?

2204
01:24:00,001 --> 01:24:02,470
It was the cold salad
hiding behind a bridal veil.

2205
01:24:02,537 --> 01:24:05,473
First off, this sauce is very savory…

2206
01:24:05,540 --> 01:24:07,675
-Savory.
-…and I love how the scallops are cooked.

2207
01:24:08,143 --> 01:24:09,611
YOU NAILED IT

2208
01:24:09,677 --> 01:24:13,448
It goes down smoothly,
and the apple adds sweetness and sourness.

2209
01:24:13,515 --> 01:24:15,150
Does it work up your appetite?

2210
01:24:15,216 --> 01:24:19,054
Yes, it feels like
I'm about to take my first step.

2211
01:24:19,120 --> 01:24:19,954
It's marriage.

2212
01:24:20,021 --> 01:24:22,257
This sauce is nice and nutty.

2213
01:24:22,323 --> 01:24:24,559
Almond milk seems suitable
to use as a sauce.

2214
01:24:24,626 --> 01:24:25,660
Yes, it goes very well.

2215
01:24:25,727 --> 01:24:28,763
Next, the chicken cake.

2216
01:24:28,830 --> 01:24:30,799
I'll try everything at once.

2217
01:24:30,865 --> 01:24:32,734
It's oddly good.

2218
01:24:32,801 --> 01:24:33,668
EATING ALL AT ONCE

2219
01:24:36,237 --> 01:24:38,740
-I can hear the crunch.
-From the celery.

2220
01:24:38,807 --> 01:24:39,641
And <i>dogani-tang.</i>

2221
01:24:39,707 --> 01:24:41,342
It's not as strong as I expected.

2222
01:24:41,409 --> 01:24:42,710
Right.

2223
01:24:42,777 --> 01:24:46,014
It's a bit bland for me,
because I like my food strong.

2224
01:24:46,314 --> 01:24:47,715
BOO

2225
01:24:47,782 --> 01:24:50,452
-That's a possibility.
-It feels like only holding hands.

2226
01:24:51,186 --> 01:24:52,921
Like nothing else will happen
at the wedding.

2227
01:24:52,987 --> 01:24:54,422
They must kiss, not just hold hands.

2228
01:24:54,489 --> 01:24:55,657
I don't think they'll kiss.

2229
01:24:55,723 --> 01:24:58,326
But she wants it to be rated R.

2230
01:24:58,393 --> 01:25:00,695
Yet it tastes like rated G for her.

2231
01:25:00,762 --> 01:25:03,498
-Rated G?
-Doesn't it taste a bit smoky though?

2232
01:25:03,565 --> 01:25:06,201
Even that smokiness
is only holding hands for me.

2233
01:25:06,267 --> 01:25:08,803
It feels like she's only holding hands.

2234
01:25:08,870 --> 01:25:11,172
This is Chef Eddie's dessert.

2235
01:25:11,239 --> 01:25:13,441
I've been curious about the strawberry.

2236
01:25:13,508 --> 01:25:14,576
And the bread.

2237
01:25:14,642 --> 01:25:17,145
She just tried the rice and strawberry.

2238
01:25:18,213 --> 01:25:20,315
Rice, bread, and strawberry.

2239
01:25:20,381 --> 01:25:22,050
They go well together.

2240
01:25:22,117 --> 01:25:23,818
-They do?
-Isn't it colorful?

2241
01:25:24,486 --> 01:25:25,687
Unfamiliar, yet harmonious?

2242
01:25:25,753 --> 01:25:26,754
Yes.

2243
01:25:27,856 --> 01:25:29,457
It feels like something will happen.

2244
01:25:29,524 --> 01:25:30,892
WHAT'S GOING ON?

2245
01:25:30,959 --> 01:25:32,327
-What?
-What will happen?

2246
01:25:32,393 --> 01:25:35,263
This is more like
butterflies in the stomach.

2247
01:25:35,330 --> 01:25:37,565
It feels like
something is about to happen?

2248
01:25:37,632 --> 01:25:39,467
You aren't supposed to eat it separately.

2249
01:25:39,534 --> 01:25:41,002
I'm almost done with it.

2250
01:25:41,636 --> 01:25:43,371
SHE KEPT ON EATING AS HYO-YEON ATE

2251
01:25:43,438 --> 01:25:45,974
-And the rice isn't too sweet…
-It's not.

2252
01:25:46,040 --> 01:25:48,109
…even though he used
both honey and condensed milk.

2253
01:25:48,176 --> 01:25:51,779
I thought it'd be really sweet,
but the fruits smell much stronger.

2254
01:25:52,046 --> 01:25:54,782
THE RICE IS JUST A SUPPORTING ROLE!

2255
01:25:54,849 --> 01:25:56,918
-Make your decision.
-This is so hard.

2256
01:25:56,985 --> 01:25:59,587
Which dish was more suitable for a party?

2257
01:25:59,654 --> 01:26:01,823
<i>Press one to choose Edward Lee.</i>

2258
01:26:01,890 --> 01:26:03,858
<i>Press two to choose Park Eun-yeong.</i>

2259
01:26:03,925 --> 01:26:05,527
Make your decision

2260
01:26:05,593 --> 01:26:07,829
and press the button!

2261
01:26:09,864 --> 01:26:12,500
-One second.
-Tiffany's choice!

2262
01:26:13,067 --> 01:26:14,802
WHO WILL IT BE?

2263
01:26:15,370 --> 01:26:16,204
I'm sorry.

2264
01:26:16,271 --> 01:26:18,006
This is really hard.

2265
01:26:18,072 --> 01:26:19,240
She hasn't chosen yet.

2266
01:26:19,307 --> 01:26:22,510
She hasn't chosen. The dishes were
completely different from each other.

2267
01:26:22,577 --> 01:26:24,946
-Should we decide in the next episode?
-No, I'll pick one.

2268
01:26:25,013 --> 01:26:27,282
-You have to do it.
-Yes.

2269
01:26:27,348 --> 01:26:29,951
-Please make your decision!
-It must be hard.

2270
01:26:30,018 --> 01:26:31,986
It's an important decision.

2271
01:26:32,053 --> 01:26:32,954
She made her choice.

2272
01:26:33,021 --> 01:26:34,789
WHO DID SHE CHOOSE?

2273
01:26:34,856 --> 01:26:36,424
The result is in.

2274
01:26:36,491 --> 01:26:38,793
-So?
-So? Who did Tiffany choose?

2275
01:26:38,860 --> 01:26:40,495
Let's find out the result!

2276
01:26:40,562 --> 01:26:41,663
Show us!

2277
01:26:42,664 --> 01:26:45,633
Tiffany the Party Girl made her decision.

2278
01:26:45,700 --> 01:26:50,405
Will Edward Lee win after his return
in eight long months?

2279
01:26:50,471 --> 01:26:52,340
Or will the bride-to-be,

2280
01:26:52,407 --> 01:26:56,945
Chef Park Eun-yeong, win, take a star
and walk down the aisle happily?

2281
01:26:57,011 --> 01:26:59,948
Who did Tiffany choose?

2282
01:27:02,317 --> 01:27:03,418
Who is it?

2283
01:27:04,719 --> 01:27:06,421
PARK EUN-YEONG WINS

2284
01:27:06,487 --> 01:27:07,755
Park Eun-yeong wins!

2285
01:27:07,989 --> 01:27:10,325
CHEF PARK EUN-YEONG'S
THE STAR IS MINE, GEE WINS

2286
01:27:10,391 --> 01:27:11,492
Park Eun-yeong wins!

2287
01:27:11,559 --> 01:27:13,294
CONGRATULATIONS

2288
01:27:13,361 --> 01:27:18,366
-Chef Eun-yeong was chosen.
-Congratulations.

2289
01:27:18,433 --> 01:27:21,002
When I imagined the party I had ahead,

2290
01:27:21,069 --> 01:27:23,304
Chef Eun-yeong's dish

2291
01:27:23,371 --> 01:27:25,306
that made me feel like

2292
01:27:25,373 --> 01:27:27,875
-we'd only hold hands and walk inside…
-The cold salad.

2293
01:27:27,942 --> 01:27:30,878
…captured my heart a little more.

2294
01:27:30,945 --> 01:27:33,982
But I personally loved your dish too.

2295
01:27:34,048 --> 01:27:37,118
Please put a star on her, Tiffany!

2296
01:27:37,685 --> 01:27:40,722
This is her fourth star.

2297
01:27:40,788 --> 01:27:42,190
Can we celebrate by dancing?

2298
01:27:42,257 --> 01:27:44,926
Please play "Gee" for them!

2299
01:27:49,297 --> 01:27:50,698
GIVING THE STAR WHILE DANCING TO "GEE"

2300
01:27:50,765 --> 01:27:53,568
Tiffany's different. She can move,
but Eun-yeong can't.

2301
01:27:53,635 --> 01:27:55,303
Congratulations, Eun-yeong!

2302
01:27:55,370 --> 01:27:58,506
TIFFANY AND EUN-YEONG,
CONGRATULATIONS ON GETTING MARRIED

2303
01:27:58,973 --> 01:28:01,242
Before, there was Girls' Generation-TTS.

2304
01:28:01,309 --> 01:28:02,510
It's our time now.

2305
01:28:02,577 --> 01:28:04,245
Shouldn't Taeyeon have a say?

2306
01:28:04,312 --> 01:28:06,214
I don't want to hear her opinion.

2307
01:28:06,481 --> 01:28:07,515
DIDN'T ASK, DON'T CARE

2308
01:28:07,582 --> 01:28:09,217
-We present her fridge!
-Fridge!

2309
01:28:09,984 --> 01:28:12,153
She has hog maw too.

2310
01:28:12,220 --> 01:28:14,055
The flavor is all on the inside.

2311
01:28:15,990 --> 01:28:17,925
Once you try it, you'll love it.

2312
01:28:17,992 --> 01:28:19,527
Once you're hooked, you only eat that.

2313
01:28:19,594 --> 01:28:20,862
I only go after one thing.

2314
01:28:21,195 --> 01:28:22,397
THE VIGOR OF THE MAIN VOCALIST

2315
01:28:22,463 --> 01:28:23,498
THIS PLAYOFF IN THE KITCHEN

2316
01:28:23,564 --> 01:28:24,532
WILL DECIDE WHO'S THE MAIN CHEF

2317
01:28:24,732 --> 01:28:26,301
CAPTURING YOUR ATTENTION

2318
01:28:26,534 --> 01:28:28,603
STRUGGLING TO BECOME THE MAIN CHEF

2319
01:28:28,670 --> 01:28:29,504
Poong!

2320
01:28:30,004 --> 01:28:31,105
THE HUNT FOR MORE AIRTIME

2321
01:28:31,339 --> 01:28:32,273
BECAME A FAN

2322
01:28:33,107 --> 01:28:34,609
-The apron!
-Is it choking you?

2323
01:28:34,676 --> 01:28:35,910
It keeps getting pulled up.

2324
01:28:35,977 --> 01:28:37,645
I've never worn an apron
that was too small!

2325
01:28:37,945 --> 01:28:39,080
BECOMING THE MAIN CHEF ISN'T EASY

2326
01:28:39,147 --> 01:28:40,348
What's it like?

2327
01:28:40,415 --> 01:28:41,249
This is it.

2328
01:28:41,316 --> 01:28:43,084
It's crazy and chaotic.

2329
01:28:43,318 --> 01:28:45,386
WHO'LL WIN THE MAIN CHEF PLAYOFF?

2330
01:28:49,991 --> 01:28:51,726
Turn. Grab your neck.

2331
01:28:51,793 --> 01:28:53,728
Drop your arm. Up, up, up.

2332
01:29:03,037 --> 01:29:08,042
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
